---
import ContentPage from '../layouts/ContentPage.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config/site';
const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: `${SITE.url}/` },
  { name: 'About', url: `${SITE.url}/about/` },
];
---
<ContentPage
  title="About Pool Shock Calculator"
  description="Who builds Pool Shock Calculator, why it exists, and how we keep the dosing math accurate and honest."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <p>
    Pool Shock Calculator exists to answer one deceptively tricky question — “how
    much shock does my pool actually need?” — without the guesswork, unit confusion,
    or one-size-fits-all charts you find elsewhere. Every dose comes from a single,
    tested calculation engine, so the number you see here is consistent no matter
    which page you land on.
  </p>

  <h2>Why we built it</h2>
  <p>
    Most shock “calculators” either assume a fixed pool size, ignore the strength of
    the product you actually own, or skip the target level entirely. That leads to
    cloudy water, bleached liners, wasted chemicals, and pools that stay green for
    days. We wanted a tool that takes your real volume, your real product, and your
    real situation, and returns an amount you can measure into a bucket.
  </p>

  <h2>How we keep it accurate</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>One tested engine:</strong> all dosing math lives in a single module covered by automated tests, calibrated against published manufacturer and industry reference points.</li>
    <li><strong>Cited standards:</strong> targets follow public health guidance and the breakpoint chlorination method used by certified pool operators. See our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a> for the full math.</li>
    <li><strong>Honest limits:</strong> we tell you when a product adds calcium or stabilizer, and we always defer to your product label for final dosing and safety.</li>
    <li><strong>Dated and versioned:</strong> our data-reviewed date and change log are shown on every calculator so you know how current the guidance is.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What this tool is not</h2>
  <p>
    We provide estimates for informational use, not professional or medical advice.
    Water chemistry varies with temperature, stabilizer levels, bather load, and
    balance, so always test your water and follow the safety directions on your
    chemical products. For persistent problems, consult a local pool professional.
  </p>

  <h2>Get in touch</h2>
  <p>
    Spotted something off, or have a product strength we should add? We genuinely
    want to know — reach us on our <a href="/contact/">contact page</a>. Corrections
    from readers are one of the ways we keep the numbers trustworthy.
  </p>
</ContentPage>
